<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Johnston, John. Description of the Country around Lakes Superior and Huron, 1809. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0018</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">of Michipaquaton in Lake Superior <span class="DelHand-author">S</span><span class="AddHand-author">A</span>long with Some Others<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  He assures me they fell in with a Small lake about 9 days march from Lake Superior Where they met with a Race of Beaver without tails Which if true, and I have no reason to doubt his Veracity, is a <span class="AddHand-author">pheno</span>m<span class="DelHand-author">i</span><span class="AddHand-author">e</span>non that will give a<span class="DelHand-author">p</span>mple matter of discussion to the Loalogists<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Some days march nearer Lake Superior one <span class="AddHand-author">of them</span> caught a Beaver with two Tails, the lesser Springing from the Root of the layer or natural tail, which is a lusus naturae never before heard of here<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  I write this the 21<sup>st</sup> March 1809 and hope to have Some Specimens of the former and the last mentioned Skin by the Middle of May next<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The greatest quantity of fish Resort to the large Rivers of Lake Superior during the proper Season<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Every Spring Vessels might be laden with the finest Sturgeon from Keeywaynan River and the Natanagan alone<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  In those of the North, Red and White Trout equally abound every Autumn<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Before I conclude this Rude and hasty Sketch I must remark that the climate of S<sup>t</sup> Marys is extremely Variable; in Summer the transitions from heat to cold are frequent and Sudden the vicissitudes are equally great in Winter, but</p>

